As I prepare to officially announce some new music (🫠🙌🏻), I want to take some time to revisit my first album. 

These songs are so special to me. The process of making them uncovered creative crevices inside me that I was previously unaware of. The fact that they resonated with so many of you is the icing on a very delicious 5 layer cello cake. 

Here’s one of my faves from the album. The first single from “Me, Myself, Myself, and I”: nature/nurture

Next up on the “Me, Myself, Myself, and I” retrospective is Thaw and Hum. I wrote this one during an epic ice storm in early 2021, aching for spring in the middle of COVID home-bound winter. I filmed the video in my ice cold garage. The things we do for art. 

I’m taking a look back at the tunes from my first album before I announce some new music 👀. Which tune should I do next?

Continuing the trip down memory lane, here is Madeline. 

I was commissioned to write this tune in memory of a friend’s grandmother. I got to write, record, and film this video in her grandmother’s actual home in Topsail Beach, NC. Needless to say, I knew I had to make this tune sound and feel like the ocean. 

New music announcement coming soon 🥹

Spinning Wheel: the tune that started it all.

In December 2020, I was in a real low spot. In an effort to pull myself out, I made myself sit down at my computer and microphone with my cello and write something. The goal was to write just a minute of music to release on social media. As I kept building this track, I quickly bypassed a minute of music, and then two, and after an hour or so of recording I realized I had a full, completed thing. I also realized that I loved what I had made and the process of making it. 

I’m grateful I had the strength to pull myself out of bed to do it. This tune really changed a whole lot for me. 

I’m revisiting the tracks from my 2021 album, “Me, Myself, Myself, and I” in preparation for the release of some new music. Stay tuned for more🙏🏻

The Listener is one of my favorite tracks from “Me, Myself, Myself, and I” to perform live. I love the mechanical nature of it - once it starts, it just rolls on until the end. It’s mesmerizing, really. 

Can’t wait to announce some new music soon. I’m quite impatient 😭

This past week I participated in @silkroadproject’s Global Musician Workshop and my life is forever changed for it. 

The workshop brought together 70 participants from almost 25 different countries to collaborate and learn from 9 all-star faculty members from vastly different musical traditions and cultures. We reached across borders to find commonalities and pushed ourselves beyond our comfort zones in order to grow as musicians and people. 

Here’s a selection of some favorite moments. It was hard to choose only 10. I think the thing I’m most proud of was writing lyrics (6) to the Mongolian melody taught to us by the wonderful @sixfingers2020 (5).

I’m so grateful to @blockcello for spearheading this magical program and for being a continuing source of inspiration in my life. 

I encourage any and all musicians to look into applying for the #globalmusicianworkshop next year. It’s really an experience unlike anything else. You will not regret it.

And while you’re at it, please consider donating some dollars to the amazing organization known as the Southern Environmental Law Center. As the largest non-profit, nonpartisan environmental legal advocacy organization rooted in and focused on the South, SELC takes on the toughest challenges to protect our air, water, land, wildlife, and people who live here. 

From cleaning up 270 tons of coal ash, to protecting the Atlantic coast from offshore drilling, to helping return red wolves to the wild, @southernenvironment is the heart behind so many landmark environmental actions, the effects of which can be felt far beyond the South. 

Please join me in helping raise funds and awareness for SELC and the important work they are doing. Consider sharing this and donating via my fundraiser on Instagram today 💙
